faces theoretical doubts. The present collection takes up the tension between the wide political use of human rights claims and the intellectual skepticism about them. In particular two major issues are identified that call for conceptual clarification in order to better understand human rights claims both in theory and in practice: the question of how to justify human rights and the tension between universal normative claims and particular moralities.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 3.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aHuman rightsxPhilosophy. 4aEthik. 4aMenschenrechte. 4aRechtfertigung. 4aUniversalismus. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh  aEthics.  aHuman Rights.  aJustification.  aUniversalism.1 aCruft, Rowan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErnst, Gerhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErnst, Gerhard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFreeman, Samuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriffin, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeilinger, Jan-Christoph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeilinger, Jan-Christoph, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHope, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMayr, Erasmus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMieth, Corinna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchaber, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTas